Fake Headline Detection

Brandon Chan

Introduction

Headlines are a problem. In today’s world, it feels like headlines are more inflamatory than informative, engineered to get a reaction. The big problem with headlines is that a lot of people read them and form an opinion without reading the article it’s attached to. It’s an even bigger problem considering the prevalence of fake news. These headlines swing the opinions of millions of people and keep people misinformed. So in writing this report, I want to learn a little more about the problem at hand, specifically, what drives the differences between real and fake headlines and how easy it is to distinguish real and fake headlines.

Goal

Find the best model to predict whether or not an article is real or fake based on the headline alone.

The Original Data

  • 44,689 article headlines
    • 21,417 real
    • 23,481 fake
    • Posted anywhere between March 2015 and February 2018

The Data I Will Be Using

  • I will be using a random sample of 2,000 out of the 44,689 articles. *My tiny 13-inch laptop simply can’t even begin to handle that much text processing on all 44,689 articles, so the actual data used will be a representative sample of the original data set.
  • 2,000 article headlines
    • 1048 real
    • 952 fake

This is a peek into the data I’ll be working with.

Processing the Data

The data in the original format is not ready for analysis.
To prepare the text for analysis I:

  • Got rid of whitespace
  • Got rid of puncuation
  • Got rid of numbers
  • Made everything lower case
  • Got rid of words with no meaning (ex. “the”, “and”, “it”, etc.)

The main purpose of this processing is to only keep the meaningful characters and words in the headlines and get rid of everything else.

Next, I tokenized the text. This means I turned headlines into a list of words. Fundamentally, all this involves, is turning a sentence string, into a list of word strings.

This results in a total of 5,527 total unique words, but I will only keep the top 1000 most frequent words. I am only keeping the top 1000 because the top 1000 words are the words that best distinguish headlines. Words outside of the top 1000 are usually just words that appear in one or two headlines total. Another reason is because of my tiny laptop. I’ve tried with all 5,527 words and my laptop crashes when fitting complex models like random forest.

Finally, I keep the top 1000 most prominent words and I calculated the TFIDF value for all 1000 words in every headline. Here, The TFIDF value simply represents the ratio of the number of times a word appears in a headline and the number of headlines that contain the word. This ratio is a great measure of how well a word distinguishes headlines. The more a word appears in a single headline, the more it distinguishes that headline. But the more a word appears in all headlines, the less it distinguishes headlines overall.

So this is the final data set I’ll be working with:

  • 2,000 rows. One for each headline.
  • 1,001 columns. 1,000 words and whether or not the article is real or fake.
  • 2,000,000 TFIDF values
df <- read.csv("C:/Users/Computadora/Documents/434 final/files/tf_idf.csv")

As you can see, almost all of the TFIDF values are 0. This is because to have a TFIDF value greater than 0, the word has to appear in the headline and most words only appear in small number of headlines.

Variable/Word Selection

Before diving into our lovely assortment of models, let’s employ a variable selection technique to find the most important predictors for the truthfullness of a headline. Our goal is to keep the variables/words that distinguish headlines, and eliminate the variables/words that add unwanted noise.

For variable/word selection, I will fit a random forest model with default parameters to all of my data, get the mean decrease in accuracy for every word and keep the top 20th percetile words. This is a generalized first step that should give us a great idea of which variables are the most impactful for predicting real or fake.

set.seed(1)
rf = randomForest(truth~.,data=df, importance =TRUE)
varImpPlot(rf)

As shown by the importance plot, the word “video” is shown to have the most influence on our predictions with a mean decrease in accuracy of 91.476. This means that removing “video” from the model results in 91.476 additional missclassifications on average, a huge amount!

mda <- importance(rf, type = 1)
df.subset <- ((df %>% select(-truth))[,which(mda > quantile(mda, 0.8))])
df.subset$truth = df$truth

Model Evalutation

Now, time for the fun part! Let’s see how all the different classification models perform on our data. For every model, I will measure performance by estimating the missclassification rate and calculating the area under the ROC curve. I will measure performance across three different training set sizes, 60% of the original data, 70%, and 80%. If a model requires hyperparamter tuning, I will test different hyperparameter values on the 70% training set, then use the resultant best hyperparameter value to evaluate performance on the other training set sizes.

For all models, I will keep the decision threshold at 0.5 because there is close to an equal amount of real and fake articles in our data.

These are the models I will be evaluating: * Logistic Regression * Linear Discriminant Analysis * Quadratic Discriminant Analysis * K-Nearest Neighbors * Classification Tree * Random Forest * Boosted Classification Tree * Neural Network * Support Vector Machine

Training Set Splits

df.subset = read.csv("C:/Users/Computadora/Documents/434 final/files/tf_idf_subset.csv")

set.seed(1)
train60_i <- sample(1:nrow(df.subset), size = round(nrow(df.subset)*0.60))
train60 <- df.subset[train60_i,]
test60 <- df.subset[-train60_i,]

train70_i <- sample(1:nrow(df.subset), size = round(nrow(df.subset)*0.7))
train70 <- df.subset[train70_i,]
test70 <- df.subset[-train70_i,]

train80_i <- sample(1:nrow(df.subset), size = round(nrow(df.subset)*0.8))
train80 <- df.subset[train80_i,]
test80 <- df.subset[-train80_i,]

train.dfs <- list(train60, train70, train80)
test.dfs <- list(test60, test70, test80)

model.results <- data.frame(Size = c("60%", "70%", "80%"),
                     Error = c(NA, NA, NA),
                     AUC = c(NA, NA, NA))

Logistic Regression

for (i in 1:3){
  logis <- glm(truth ~ ., data = train.dfs[[i]], family = "binomial")
  
  prob <- predict(logis, test.dfs[[i]], type = "response")
  pred <- ifelse(prob > 0.5, "real", "fake")
  error <- mean(pred != test.dfs[[i]]$truth)
  
  model.results$Error[i] <- error
  model.results$AUC[i] <- auc(as.numeric(test.dfs[[i]]$truth == "real"), as.numeric(pred == "real"))
}

model.results

ks <- c(2, 3, 4, seq(5, 100, 5))

Classification Tree

tree =tree(truth~., train70)

Boosted Classification Tree

Now, let’s try different values of the shrinkage parameter \(\lambda\) and see which value results in the lowest validation set error.

lambdas <- c(.0001, .001, .1, .3, .5)
errors <- c()

for (i in 1:length(lambdas)) {
    boost <- gbm(truth~., 
                 data = train70 %>% mutate(truth = as.numeric(truth == "real")), 
                 distribution = "bernoulli", 
                 n.trees = 1000, 
                 shrinkage = lambdas[i])
    
    prob <- predict(boost, 
                    newdata = test70 %>% mutate(truth = as.numeric(truth == "real")), 
                    n.trees = 1000,
                    type = "response")
    
    pred <- ifelse(prob > 0.5, "real", "fake")
    
    errors[i] <- mean(pred != test70$truth)
}
ggplot(, aes(x = lambdas, y = errors)) + geom_line() +
  ggtitle("Shrinkage Parameter Tuning") +
  xlab("Lambda") +
  ylab("Test Error")

A shrinkage parameter value of 0.3 results in the lowest validation set error.

for (i in 1:3){
  boost <- gbm(truth~., 
                 data = train.dfs[[i]] %>% mutate(truth = as.numeric(truth == "real")), 
                 distribution = "bernoulli", 
                 n.trees = 1000, 
                 shrinkage = 0.3)
    
  prob <- predict(boost, 
                    newdata = test.dfs[[i]] %>% mutate(truth = as.numeric(truth == "real")), 
                    n.trees = 1000,

Results

First, let’s look at how model performance changes as the size of the training set changes. Specifically, we’re going to average performance metrics across all models and plot it against training set size.

ggplot(results %>% group_by(Size) %>% summarise(`Average Test Error` = mean(Error)),
       aes(x = Size, y = `Average Test Error`, group = 1)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  ggtitle("Average Test Error and Training Set Size") +
  xlab("Training Set Size")

ggplot(results %>% group_by(Size) %>% summarise(`Average AUC` = mean(AUC)),
       aes(x = Size, y = `Average AUC`, group = 1)) +
  geom_line() +
  geom_point() +
  ggtitle("Average Area Under ROC Curve and Training Set Size") +
  xlab("Training Set Size")

Key Takeaways

  • Model performance increases as training set size increases.
    • Test Error decreases
    • AUC increases
  • Higher training set size means more data for models to learn from. More data to learn from means better model performance.
ggplot(results, aes(fill = Size, x = factor(Method, level = unique(Method)), y = Error)) +

Key Takeaways

  • Congratulations to the Support Vector Machine for being the best performing model!
    • Highest AUC out of all models
    • Tied with Boosted Classification Trees and Neural Networks for the lowest test error
  • Classification Trees are garbage.
    • Highest test error and lowest AUC by far
    • But hey, at least its iNTerPreTaBLe
  • Overall test errors are generally low and AUC is generally high across the board. Almost all models accurately predicted real or fake more than 85% of the time. Considering much of the model tuning is super barebones, it shows that fake headlines are easily distinguishable from real headlines.

Conclusion

We should be able to spot fake headlines from a mile away. You know its bad when a single classification tree almost reaches 80% accuracy. In our initial exploration of the data, we were able to see the big difference between fake and real headlines. Fake headlines entice the reader with videos and divisive public figures, probably because the headlines are so egregious that they need to claim video evidence. Real headlines tend have a more informative tone and purpose, covering variety of topics. The models we tested were able to pick up on those differences easily with the best models almost reaching 90% predictive accuracy. Even when only using 4% of the 44,689 total headlines we could have used, the models are still able to perform.
